Based on the aforementioned results, a plausible anti-abiotic stress mechanism can be proposed (
                        Scheme 2
                        ). Salinity stress can lead to the over-accumulation of ROS, causing oxidative damage that degrades the cell membrane and compromises its integrity [3]. It is worth noting that in plant cells, ROS are mainly produced by chloroplasts, mitochondria, and the apoplast [14]. The small-sized ZnPB can penetrate the wheat seed coat and enter the seed tissues. It can also enter leaves through leaf stomata and cuticular pathways, ultimately reaching the plant cell and directly eliminating intracellular ROS. Considering that ROS accumulation is the main factor causing abiotic stress in plants, the elimination of intracellular ROS can relieve the physiological changes induced by salinity stress, thereby reducing the need for plant cells to produce additional osmolytes to counter osmotic stress [45]. Second, accompanying the decline of ROS, the ROS-activated nonselective cation channels (ROS-NSCC) in the wheat plasma membrane could be enhanced, improving the cell's K+ retention ability and reducing K+ efflux rate [46]. Third, the imbalance of cellular Na+ homeostasis under salinity stress can be counteracted through the coordination of Ca2+ sensing and transduction pathways on cell membrane pumps and transcription factors involved in gene expression regulation. Consequently, this leads to the efflux of excess Na+ from the cytosol. We observed that the change in Ca2+ levels in the straw under different treatments exhibited a similar trend as the results of Na+ and K+ (Fig. S7). As verified by An et al. [45], it can be attributed to the down-regulation of cation exchanger (CAX1) gene GhCAX1 (Gh_D01G0422), thus increasing the cytosolic Ca2+ level and Na+ efflux efficiency.
